00:24:39,260 --> 00:24:43,300
 He does do that for tax collectors and liars

530
00:24:43,300 --> 00:24:46,340
 and people who look at pornography and addicts

531
00:24:46,340 --> 00:24:50,360
 and drunkards and every other vice you can imagine.

532
00:24:50,360 --> 00:24:52,280
 That's what he does.

533
00:24:52,280 --> 00:24:56,320
 The point of this is that when we come needy,

534
00:24:56,320 --> 00:24:58,560
 he responds no matter who we are.

535
00:24:58,560 --> 00:25:00,520
 That's the point, do you see that?

536
00:25:00,520 --> 00:25:06,980
 The problem is, most of us, if we're just being real,

537
00:25:06,980 --> 00:25:10,060
 most of us don't see ourselves that way.

538
00:25:10,060 --> 00:25:12,200
 We can even kind of get down with that,

539
00:25:12,200 --> 00:25:15,560
 the abstract idea of God being a merciful God like that,

540
00:25:15,560 --> 00:25:19,600
 but we don't see ourselves as being needy.

541
00:25:19,600 --> 00:25:23,360
 We tend to be a lot more like the Pharisee in this story,

542
00:25:23,360 --> 00:25:27,520
 right, looking at our own record to justify us.

543
00:25:27,520 --> 00:25:28,600
 That's what's happening here.

544
00:25:28,600 --> 00:25:31,560
 But Jesus shows us that what we need

545
00:25:31,560 --> 00:25:34,340
 is not to act like we have it all together,

546
00:25:34,340 --> 00:25:39,280
 but rather to admit we are morally bankrupt

547
00:25:39,280 --> 00:25:41,820
 to finally own it.

548
00:25:41,820 --> 00:25:43,180
 That's what he's inviting us to.

549
00:25:43,180 --> 00:25:47,180
 I remember it was, I think it was 10 years ago now.

550
00:25:47,180 --> 00:25:49,260
 I was at a gas station with my wife.

